  • Section 376: Punishment for rape

  • Section 420: Cheating and dishonestly inducing delivery of property

  • Section 155: Information in non-cognizable cases
  • Section 161: Examination of witnesses by police
  • Section 167: Procedure when investigation cannot be completed in twenty-four hours

2. Criminal Analysis

The FIR serves as the foundation for initiating criminal proceedings. It is crucial for establishing the basic facts of the case and the nature of the allegations against the accused. The FIR must contain: - The name of the complainant - The details of the offense - The time and place of the occurrence - The names of the accused, if known

3. Case Law Integration

4. Procedural Guidance

5. Bail Considerations

  • Bailable Offenses: The accused is entitled to bail as a matter of right.
  • Non-Bailable Offenses: The court has discretion to grant bail, considering factors such as the severity of the offense, the likelihood of the accused fleeing, and the potential for tampering with evidence.

6. Rights Protection

  • The accused has the right to legal representation at all stages of the proceedings.
  • Under Article 10-A of the Constitution of Pakistan, every individual has the right to a fair trial.
  • The accused should be informed of the charges against them and have the opportunity to present a defense.

7. Evidence Requirements

  • Evidentiary Standards: The prosecution must prove the case beyond a reasonable doubt. This includes:
  • Witness testimonies

8. Practical Guidance
